===Etymology 1===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*swer-|id=swear}}
From {{inh|en|enm|sweren}}, {{m|enm|swerien}}, from {{inh|en|ang|swerian|t=to swear, take an oath of office}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*swarjan}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*swarjaną|t=to speak, swear}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*swer-|t=to swear}}.

Cognate with {{cog|fy|swarre|t=to swear}}, {{cog|stq|swera|t=to swear}}, {{cog|nl|zweren|t=to swear, vow}}, {{cog|nds|swören|t=to swear}}, {{m|nds|sweren}}, {{cog|de|schwören|t=to swear}}, {{cog|da|sværge}}, {{cog|sv|svära|t=to swear}}, {{cog|is|sverja|t=to swear}}, {{cog|ru|свара|t=quarrel}}. Also cognate to {{cog|sq|var|t=to hang, consider, to depend from}} through Proto-Indo-European.

The original sense in all Germanic languages is “to take an oath”. The sense “to use bad language” developed in Middle English and is based on the Christian prohibition against swearing in general (cf. {{w|Gospel of Matthew|Matthew}} 5:33-37) and invoking God’s name in particular (i.e. frequent swearing was considered similar to the use of obscene words).

